These two event types serve different purposes:

**`sp.AnimationEventType.COMPLETE`** fires when an animation finishes one full playback cycle. For looping animations, it fires at the end of every loop iteration. For non-looping animations, it fires once when the animation reaches its end.

**`sp.AnimationEventType.END`** fires when an animation is stopped or replaced. This happens when you call `clearTrack()`, `clearTracks()`, or `setAnimation()` on the same track (which replaces the current animation). It does NOT fire when an animation simply reaches its end naturally.

```typescript
hero.setAnimationListener(this, (track, type, event) => {
    if (type === sp.AnimationEventType.COMPLETE) {
        // Looping 'run': fires every loop cycle
        // Non-looping 'attack': fires once at the end
        cc.log('Completed cycle: ' + track.animation.name);
    }
    if (type === sp.AnimationEventType.END) {
        // Fires when animation is interrupted/replaced
        cc.log('Ended/interrupted: ' + track.animation.name);
    }
});

hero.setAnimation(0, 'run', true);
// COMPLETE fires every loop...
hero.setAnimation(0, 'idle', true);  // END fires for 'run'
```

Use COMPLETE to react when an animation finishes (e.g., return to idle after attack). Use END to clean up when an animation is interrupted.

instruction:
Review this touch handling code and identify potential problems:

```typescript
class Slider extends cc.Sprite {
    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        cc.eventManager.addListener({
            event: cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE,
            onTouchBegan: function(touch, event) {
                this.startDrag(touch.getLocation());
                return true;
            },
            onTouchMoved: function(touch, event) {
                this.updateDrag(touch.getLocation());
            }
        }, this);
    }
}
```

output:
Issues found:

1. **`this` context is wrong.** Using `function()` instead of arrow functions means `this` inside the callbacks does NOT refer to the `Slider` instance — it refers to the listener object or `undefined` in strict mode. Calling `this.startDrag()` and `this.updateDrag()` will crash.

2. **No listener cleanup.** No `onExit` to remove the listener.

3. **Missing `swallowTouches`.** Touches will propagate to nodes behind the slider.

Fixed code:
```typescript
class Slider extends cc.Sprite {
    private _listener: cc.EventListener;

    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        this._listener = cc.eventManager.addListener({
            event: cc.EventListener.TOUCH_ONE_BY_ONE,
            swallowTouches: true,
            onTouchBegan: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.Event): boolean => {
                // Arrow function preserves `this` as the Slider instance
                this.startDrag(touch.getLocation());
                return true;
            },
            onTouchMoved: (touch: cc.Touch, event: cc.EventTouch): void => {
                this.updateDrag(touch.getLocation());
            }
        }, this);
    }

    onExit(): void {
        cc.eventManager.removeListener(this._listener);
        super.onExit();
    }
}
```

Always use arrow functions (`=>`) in event listener callbacks when you need to access the enclosing class instance.

