Schedule a per-frame check comparing bounding boxes:

```typescript
class GameLayer extends cc.Layer {
    private player: cc.Sprite;
    private enemies: cc.Sprite[] = [];

    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        this.player = new cc.Sprite('hero.png');
        this.player.setPosition(240, 50);
        this.addChild(this.player);

        this.scheduleUpdate();
    }

    update(dt: number): void {
        const playerRect = this.player.getBoundingBoxToWorld();

        for (let i = this.enemies.length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
            const enemy = this.enemies[i];
            const enemyRect = enemy.getBoundingBoxToWorld();

            if (cc.rectIntersectsRect(playerRect, enemyRect)) {
                this.onCollision(enemy);
                enemy.removeFromParent(true);
                this.enemies.splice(i, 1);
            }
        }
    }

    onCollision(enemy: cc.Sprite): void {
        cc.log('Hit enemy: ' + enemy.getName());
    }
}
```

`startAnimation` and `stopAnimation` control the main loop:

```typescript
// Stop the main loop (stops rendering and updates)
cc.director.stopAnimation();

// Restart the main loop
cc.director.startAnimation();
```

These are lower-level than `pause()`/`resume()`. Stopping animation completely halts the game loop:

```typescript
// Difference from pause:
// pause() — stops scheduler and actions, continues rendering
// stopAnimation() — stops everything including rendering

// Use case: app going to background
class AppLifecycle {
    static onEnterBackground(): void {
        cc.director.stopAnimation();
        cc.log('App backgrounded, animation stopped');
    }

    static onEnterForeground(): void {
        cc.director.startAnimation();
        cc.log('App foregrounded, animation resumed');
    }
}

// Use case: power saving when idle
class IdleDetector {
    private _idleTime: number = 0;
    private static readonly IDLE_THRESHOLD = 30; // seconds
    private _animationStopped: boolean = false;

    update(dt: number): void {
        this._idleTime += dt;
        if (this._idleTime > IdleDetector.IDLE_THRESHOLD && !this._animationStopped) {
            cc.director.stopAnimation();
            this._animationStopped = true;
        }
    }

    onUserInput(): void {
        this._idleTime = 0;
        if (this._animationStopped) {
            cc.director.startAnimation();
            this._animationStopped = false;
        }
    }
}
```

```typescript
class GlowEffect extends cc.Layer {
    private _glowDraw: cc.DrawNode;
    private _normalDraw: cc.DrawNode;

    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();

        // Background sprite
        const bg = new cc.Sprite('res/bg_dark.png');
        bg.setPosition(240, 160);
        this.addChild(bg);

        // Normal draw node (standard alpha blending)
        this._normalDraw = new cc.DrawNode();
        this.addChild(this._normalDraw, 1);

        // Glow draw node (additive blending)
        this._glowDraw = new cc.DrawNode();
        this._glowDraw.setBlendFunc(cc.SRC_ALPHA, cc.ONE);
        this.addChild(this._glowDraw, 2);

        this.drawScene();
    }

    private drawScene(): void {
        const center = cc.p(240, 160);

        // Solid circle (normal blending)
        this._normalDraw.drawCircle(
            center, 30, 0, 32, false, 2,
            cc.color(255, 200, 0, 255)
        );

        // Glow halo (additive — brightens underlying pixels)
        for (let i = 3; i >= 1; i--) {
            const r = 30 + i * 20;
            const alpha = Math.floor(60 / i);
            this._glowDraw.drawDot(
                center, r,
                cc.color(255, 150, 0, alpha)
            );
        }
    }
}
```

Additive blending (`SRC_ALPHA, ONE`) adds the drawn color to whatever is behind it, creating a glow. Using multiple concentric translucent dots with decreasing alpha produces a soft halo effect on top of the normal scene.

instruction:
Find and fix the bug in this local storage code:

```typescript
class ScoreManager {
    saveHighScore(score: number): void {
        const current = cc.sys.localStorage.getItem('highscore');
        if (score > current) {
            cc.sys.localStorage.setItem('highscore', score);
        }
    }
}
```

output:
Two bugs:

**Bug 1: String comparison instead of number comparison.** `getItem` returns a `string | null | undefined`. Comparing a `number` with a `string` using `>` gives unreliable results (e.g., `"9" > 100` is `false` but `"9" > "100"` would depend on string ordering).

**Bug 2: No null check.** If no highscore exists yet, `current` is `null`, and `score > null` coerces `null` to `0` which works accidentally, but is fragile.

Fixed code:
```typescript
class ScoreManager {
    saveHighScore(score: number): void {
        const raw = cc.sys.localStorage.getItem('highscore');
        const current: number = raw ? parseInt(raw, 10) : 0;
        if (score > current) {
            cc.sys.localStorage.setItem('highscore', score.toString());
            cc.log('New high score:', score);
        }
    }

    getHighScore(): number {
        const raw = cc.sys.localStorage.getItem('highscore');
        return raw ? parseInt(raw, 10) : 0;
    }
}
```

Always parse `getItem` results to the correct type before comparison, and always convert values to strings before calling `setItem`.

