Cocos2d-x provides three logging levels:

```typescript
// Info-level log
cc.log('Player score:', 100, 'Level:', 5);

// Warning log
cc.warn('Texture not found, using fallback:', textureName);

// Error log
cc.error('Failed to load level data:', err);

// Assertion (logs error if condition is false)
cc.assert(health >= 0, 'Health cannot be negative');

// Format string utility
const msg = cc.formatStr('Player %s scored %d points', 'Alice', 100);
cc.log(msg);
```

Practical usage pattern:
```typescript
class GameManager {
    loadLevel(id: number): void {
        cc.log('Loading level', id);
        cc.loader.loadJson('res/levels/level' + id + '.json', (err, data) => {
            if (err) {
                cc.error('Failed to load level', id, err);
                return;
            }
            if (!data.enemies) {
                cc.warn('Level', id, 'has no enemy data');
            }
            cc.log('Level', id, 'loaded successfully');
        });
    }
}
```

All logging functions accept variadic arguments (`...args: any[]`).

Use `cc.GLProgram` to compile and link custom vertex and fragment shaders:

```typescript
// Vertex shader
const vertSrc = `
    attribute vec4 a_position;
    attribute vec2 a_texCoord;
    varying vec2 v_texCoord;
    void main() {
        gl_Position = CC_PMatrix * CC_MVMatrix * a_position;
        v_texCoord = a_texCoord;
    }
`;

// Fragment shader (grayscale effect)
const fragSrc = `
    precision mediump float;
    varying vec2 v_texCoord;
    uniform sampler2D CC_Texture0;
    void main() {
        vec4 color = texture2D(CC_Texture0, v_texCoord);
        float gray = dot(color.rgb, vec3(0.299, 0.587, 0.114));
        gl_FragColor = vec4(vec3(gray), color.a);
    }
`;

// Create and initialize
const program = new cc.GLProgram();
program.initWithString(vertSrc, fragSrc);
program.addAttribute(cc.ATTRIBUTE_NAME_POSITION, cc.VERTEX_ATTRIB_POSITION);
program.addAttribute(cc.ATTRIBUTE_NAME_TEX_COORD, cc.VERTEX_ATTRIB_TEX_COORDS);
program.link();
program.updateUniforms();

// Apply to a sprite
sprite.setShaderProgram(program);
```

The shader uses Cocos2d-x built-in uniforms `CC_PMatrix` and `CC_MVMatrix` for projection and model-view matrices.

instruction:
Find the bug in this code that registers a keyboard listener for Escape to pause the game:

```typescript
class GameScene extends cc.Scene {
    private _paused: boolean = false;

    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        cc.eventManager.addListener({
            event: cc.EventListener.KEYBOARD,
            onKeyReleased: (keyCode: cc.KEY, event: cc.Event) => {
                if (keyCode === cc.KEY.Escape) {
                    this._paused = !this._paused;
                    if (this._paused) cc.director.pause();
                    else cc.director.resume();
                }
            }
        }, this);
    }
}
```

output:
The bug is `cc.KEY.Escape` — the correct constant is `cc.KEY.escape` (lowercase 'e'). Cocos2d-x key constants use lowercase names.

Also: the listener reference is not stored, and there's no `onExit` cleanup.

Fixed code:
```typescript
class GameScene extends cc.Scene {
    private _paused: boolean = false;
    private _listener: cc.EventListener;

    onEnter(): void {
        super.onEnter();
        this._listener = cc.eventManager.addListener({
            event: cc.EventListener.KEYBOARD,
            onKeyReleased: (keyCode: cc.KEY, event: cc.Event): void => {
                if (keyCode === cc.KEY.escape) { // FIX: lowercase 'escape'
                    this._paused = !this._paused;
                    if (this._paused) {
                        cc.director.pause();
                    } else {
                        cc.director.resume();
                    }
                }
            }
        }, this);
    }

    onExit(): void {
        cc.eventManager.removeListener(this._listener);
        if (this._paused) {
            cc.director.resume(); // ensure game is not left paused
        }
        super.onExit();
    }
}
```

Common lowercase key constants: `cc.KEY.escape` (27), `cc.KEY.space` (32), `cc.KEY.enter` (13), `cc.KEY.tab` (9), `cc.KEY.backspace` (8).

```typescript
const a = cc.p(1, 0);  // right
const b = cc.p(0, 1);  // up

// Dot product
const dot: number = cc.pDot(a, b);  // 0 (perpendicular)

// Angle between two vectors (in radians)
const angle: number = cc.pAngle(a, b);  // ~1.5708 (PI/2 = 90 degrees)

// Practical: check if target is in front of player
const playerDir = cc.pNormalize(cc.p(1, 0)); // facing right
const toTarget = cc.pNormalize(cc.pSub(targetPos, playerPos));
const dotProduct = cc.pDot(playerDir, toTarget);
if (dotProduct > 0.5) {
    cc.log('Target is roughly in front (within ~60 degree cone)');
}

// Practical: angle between direction vectors
const angleDeg = cc.pAngle(playerDir, toTarget) * cc.DEG;
cc.log('Angle to target:', angleDeg, 'degrees');
```

Signatures:
```typescript
cc.pDot(v1: cc.Point, v2: cc.Point): number
cc.pAngle(a: cc.Point, b: cc.Point): number  // returns radians
```

`switchToAndReleaseMe(n)` switches to layer at index `n` AND releases (frees memory of) the currently displayed layer:

```typescript
const mainLayer = new cc.Layer();
const tutorialLayer = new cc.Layer();
const multiplex = new cc.LayerMultiplex(mainLayer, tutorialLayer);
scene.addChild(multiplex);

// Show tutorial first
multiplex.switchTo(1);

// Switch to main and release tutorial (one-time screen)
multiplex.switchToAndReleaseMe(0);
// tutorialLayer is now released and cannot be switched back to
```

**`switchTo(n)`** — shows layer `n`, hides current. The current layer remains in memory and can be switched back to later.

**`switchToAndReleaseMe(n)`** — shows layer `n`, removes AND releases the current layer. Use this when the current layer won't be needed again (e.g., one-time tutorial, loading screen).

Use `switchTo` for screens you revisit (main menu, settings). Use `switchToAndReleaseMe` for one-time screens to save memory.

Use the `cc.LayerColor` constructor with a `cc.Color` argument:

```typescript
// Full-screen black background
const bg = new cc.LayerColor(cc.color(0, 0, 0, 255));
scene.addChild(bg, -1);

// Custom-sized red layer
const redBox = new cc.LayerColor(cc.color(255, 0, 0, 255), 200, 100);
redBox.setPosition(100, 100);
this.addChild(redBox);

// Using static factory method
const blueLayer = cc.LayerColor.create(cc.color(0, 0, 255, 255));
this.addChild(blueLayer);
```

`cc.LayerColor` extends `cc.Layer` and draws a solid color rectangle. The constructor accepts `(color)` for a full-screen layer, or `(color, width, height)` for a custom-sized one. Color values use RGBA 0–255 range.

Use the setter methods or direct property access to modify gradient colors and opacity at runtime:

```typescript
const grad = new cc.LayerGradient(
    cc.color(255, 0, 0, 255),
    cc.color(0, 0, 255, 255)
);
this.addChild(grad);

// Using setter methods
grad.setStartColor(cc.color(0, 255, 0, 255));
grad.setEndColor(cc.color(255, 255, 0, 255));
grad.setStartOpacity(255);
grad.setEndOpacity(128);
grad.setVector(cc.p(1, -1));  // diagonal direction

// Using properties
grad.startColor = cc.color(100, 50, 200, 255);
grad.endColor = cc.color(20, 10, 50, 255);
grad.startOpacity = 255;
grad.endOpacity = 200;

// Read current values
const start = grad.getStartColor();
const end = grad.getEndColor();
const dir = grad.getVector();
```

Opacity values range from 0–255. The vector changes the gradient direction without recreating the layer.

`cc.FLT_EPSILON` is a very small number used for safe floating-point comparisons:

```typescript
// Bad: direct equality check (unreliable with floats)
if (value === 0) { /* may fail */ }

// Good: epsilon comparison
if (Math.abs(value) < cc.FLT_EPSILON) {
    cc.log('Value is effectively zero');
}

// Common use: avoid dividing by zero vectors
const len = cc.pLength(direction);
if (len > cc.FLT_EPSILON) {
    const normalized = cc.pNormalize(direction);
    node.setPosition(cc.pAdd(pos, cc.pMult(normalized, speed * dt)));
}

// Compare two floating point values
function floatEquals(a: number, b: number): boolean {
    return Math.abs(a - b) < cc.FLT_EPSILON;
}
```

instruction:
Find and fix the bug in this code that tries to blend two animations:

```typescript
const hero = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas');
hero.setMix('walk', 'run', 0.3);
hero.setAnimation(0, 'run', true);
// Later...
hero.setAnimation(0, 'walk', true); // Expected smooth blend, but it snaps
```

output:
The bug is that `setMix` was set for 'walk' -> 'run' but the actual transition is 'run' -> 'walk'. `setMix` is directional — it only defines the blend for the specified from->to pair.

**Fixed code:**
```typescript
const hero = new sp.SkeletonAnimation('res/hero/hero.json', 'res/hero/hero.atlas');

// Define both directions
hero.setMix('walk', 'run', 0.3);
hero.setMix('run', 'walk', 0.3);  // Added: reverse direction

hero.setAnimation(0, 'run', true);
// Later...
hero.setAnimation(0, 'walk', true); // Now blends smoothly over 0.3s
```

`setMix('walk', 'run', 0.3)` only applies when transitioning FROM walk TO run. To get smooth transitions in both directions, you must call `setMix` for each direction explicitly.

`ccs.Armature.getBoundingBox()` and a regular `cc.Node.getBoundingBox()` differ in how they compute the rectangle:

**cc.Node.getBoundingBox()**
- Based on the node's `contentSize`, `position`, `anchor`, `scale`, and `rotation`
- Returns a fixed-size rect that doesn't change with animation
- Cheap to compute

**ccs.Armature.getBoundingBox()**
- Recalculates from all bone positions on every call
- Returns a rect that encompasses all visible bones in their current animation pose
- Changes shape as the animation plays (e.g., wider during an attack swing)
- More expensive to compute

```typescript
const armature = ccs.Armature.create('hero');
armature.animation.play('idle', -1, -1);

// This rect changes based on current animation frame
const idleBox: cc.Rect = armature.getBoundingBox();

armature.animation.play('attack', -1, 0);
// After switching to attack, the bounding box may be wider
// because the arm extends outward
const attackBox: cc.Rect = armature.getBoundingBox();
```

Because of the per-call recalculation cost, avoid calling `getBoundingBox()` every frame on many armatures. Cache the result or use it only for broad-phase collision checks.

Create a silhouette by zeroing out the source color and using only the destination:

```typescript
// Method 1: Use a shader to force black color, then normal blend
class SilhouetteSprite extends cc.Sprite {
    constructor(filename: string) {
        super(filename);
        this.initSilhouetteShader();
    }

    private initSilhouetteShader(): void {
        const fragSrc = `
            precision mediump float;
            varying vec2 v_texCoord;
            uniform sampler2D CC_Texture0;
            uniform vec4 u_shadowColor;
            void main() {
                vec4 tex = texture2D(CC_Texture0, v_texCoord);
                gl_FragColor = vec4(u_shadowColor.rgb, tex.a * u_shadowColor.a);
            }
        `;

        const program = new cc.GLProgram();
        program.initWithString(DEFAULT_VERT, fragSrc);
        program.addAttribute(cc.ATTRIBUTE_NAME_POSITION, cc.VERTEX_ATTRIB_POSITION);
        program.addAttribute(cc.ATTRIBUTE_NAME_TEX_COORD, cc.VERTEX_ATTRIB_TEX_COORDS);
        program.link();
        program.updateUniforms();
        this.setShaderProgram(program);

        // Set shadow color (dark, semi-transparent)
        const state = this.getGLProgramState();
        state.setUniformVec4('u_shadowColor', { x: 0.0, y: 0.0, z: 0.0, w: 0.5 });
    }
}

// Method 2: Simple approach using setColor + blend
function createSimpleShadow(originalSprite: cc.Sprite): cc.Sprite {
    const shadow = new cc.Sprite(originalSprite.getTexture());
    shadow.setColor(cc.color(0, 0, 0));
    shadow.setOpacity(80);
    shadow.setBlendFunc(new cc.BlendFunc(cc.SRC_ALPHA, cc.ONE_MINUS_SRC_ALPHA));
    shadow.setPosition(originalSprite.x + 5, originalSprite.y - 5);
    shadow.setScale(originalSprite.getScale());
    return shadow;
}
```

